lend of sixteenth century visual and archival evidence, it examines how individuals and families at artisanal levels (such as shoemakers, barbers, bakers and innkeepers) lived and worked, managed their household economies and consumption, socialised in their homes, and engaged with the arts and the markets for luxury goods. It demonstrates that although the economic and social status of local craftsmen and traders was relatively low, their material possessions show how these men and women who rarely make it into the history books were fully engaged with contemporary culture, cultural customs and the urban way of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArtisanszItalyzSienaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMaterial culturezItalyzSienaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMiddle classzItalyzSienaxHistoryy16th century. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aEarly modern artisans and shopkeepers.  aEarly modern material culture and daily life.  aHistory of Siena.  aItalian Renaissance.  aMaterial culture and consumer history.  aRenaissance domestic interior and decorative arts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048550265?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048550265423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048550265/original  a978-3-11-0689